pullRequest.body:
We refactor the `StrictSegal` infrastructure, making two notable changes:
- The `StrictSegal` class is redefined as a structure, and the class `IsStrictSegal X : Prop` is added in its place.
- `Path`, `StrictSegal`, and related constructions are defined for truncated simplicial sets. A path in a simplicial set `X` is then defined as a 1-truncated path in the 1-truncation of `X`. 

---

If I'm reading this correct, `StrictSegal X` is the structure of an (n + 1)-StrictSegal structure on the (n+1)-truncation of `X` for all `n`. If this is right, this feels very redundant because we're specifying explicit equivalences for each map `X.spine m : X _[m]‚ÜíPath X m` infinitely many times (for each `n` so that `m ‚â§ n + 1`). 

The code you've deleted specifies each equivalence exactly once. Is there a way to do this while re-using the truncated versions of the code?

This also surprises me a bit. One thought is that this redundancy is removed if `Truncated.StrictSegal` is defined such that an `n + 1`-truncated simplicial set `X` is `Truncated.StrictSegal` when its `n + 1`-simplices are uniquely determined by their spine (rather than its `m`-simplices for all `m ‚â§ n + 1`). But, this still strikes me as the wrong definition for the truncated case.

Relatedly, I was surprised that I never needed any sort of proof that the `StrictSegal` data at each truncation level agreed with the data from the lower truncation levels. I will give this all some more thought.

Yes, I agree that's the wrong definition in the truncated case. Though perhaps `Truncated.StrictSegal` could be defined such that an `n + 1`-truncated simplicial set `X` is `Truncated.StrictSegal` when its `n + 1`-simplices are uniquely determined by their spine AND its further `n`-truncation is `Truncated.StrictSegal` (inductively now in `n`).
But let's let @joelriou weigh in.
@emilyriehl I believe you have stated a better definition here. I am still working on the best way to define this in lean.

I would think the easiest approach would be to keep the "old" definition of `StrictSegal`, and to define `X.StrictSegal` for `X : SSet.Truncated (n + 1)` by using mostly the same definition in dimensions in `m ‚â§ n + 1`. I do not think it is a problem if we have no definition of `StrictSegal` for `0`-truncated simplicial sets...

@joelriou this is extremely helpful, thank you. If I understand your suggestion correctly, it corresponds approximately to what's here now (commit [4abc0d6](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/20668/commits/4abc0d6953abe8b850d5f30603d5c604ad24932e)). I am working on an alternative definition that I believe corresponds more closely to @emilyriehl's suggestion above. I will open a PR for comparison.
No, because you have changed the definition of `SSet.StrictSegal`, which seems unnecessary to me.
My mistake. Are you suggesting that `SSet.StrictSegal` not be defined in terms of `SSet.Truncated.StrictSegal`?
#21105 provides a prototype of a definition more in line with that suggested by @emilyriehl above.

Yes, I was suggesting not changing the definition of `SSet.StrictSegal`, and not using induction. The inductive definition seems a little bit unnecessarily complicated to me (for example: you have to struggle with `trunc`, which would not happen with the more direct definition).
(If we want to provide an "inductive" constructor for `Truncated.StrictSegal` and `SSet.StrictSegal`, I would rather see this as an additional definition which would have as inputs bijections which express that there is a unique way to glue a path of length `1` and a path of length `n` with compatible extremities in order to obtain a path of length `n + 1` (similarly as `ComposableArrows.precomp`)).
My overall suggestion is: keep things simple!

Agreed, simple is good!

For what it's worth, I actually think that the existence of `StrictSegal.trunc` in #21105 solved one of the big issues with the definition here. In a lemma like `spine_Œ¥_arrow_eq` in which the `StrictSegal` data from two different truncation levels is used, `trunc` allowed specifying this in a way which translated much better to the untruncated form of the lemma.

I had not considered implementing two independent definitions of `StrictSegal`. I think you are correct that this will prove much simpler. While I think it will require duplicating some proofs, resorting to copy-paste is not so bad in my opinion. My only real concern is that it may lead to the proliferation of translations between the two notions as we begin to define more constructions on both `SSet` and `SSet.Truncated`.

I will work on implementing the approach you mention so that we have a diff to work with.
#21146 provides a definition of `SSet.StrictSegal` that is independent of `SSet.Truncated.StrictSegal`.
Marking this as resolved since `SSet.StrictSegal` is now defined independently of `SSet.Truncated.StrictSegal`. Thanks for the great feedback on this thread!
Does it make sense that we would take the `n`-spine in a simplicial set `X` via the `n + 1`-truncation of `X`? Or perhaps the spine should just not be defined for `n = 0`?
I'm unsure about the name `Hom.tr`. I chose not to use `mk`, as in my mind `SimplexCategory.Truncated.Hom.mk` would logically take an `OrderHom` rather than a `SimplexCategory` morphism.
This seems reasonable to me if the mathlib experts approve.

Because `Path` is defined here in terms of `Truncated.Path` rather than using `Truncated.Path‚ÇÅ` directly, it unfolds to `((Truncated.trunc 1 1).obj ((truncation 1).obj X)).Path‚ÇÅ n`. 

While this is defeq to `((truncation 1).obj X).Path‚ÇÅ n`, it is at the very least confusing to see the extra layer of truncation in the infoview. 

Unfortunately, the only obvious solution I see is to define `SSet.Path` directly in terms of `Path‚ÇÅ`, which I think means duplicating all of the `Truncated.Path` constructions on `Path‚ÇÅ`, as was done before @joelriou suggested a way to cut down on this duplication.

Is there a better solution (and is it worth implementing)?

We should not have to see any `Path‚ÇÅ` in the infoview. Once a reasonable API is developed for `Truncated.Path` (I think you should add abbreviations `Truncated.Path.vertex/arrow` similarly as the definitions you have done for `SSet.Path`), you may define `SSet.Path` as an abbrev (for `Truncated.Path` of the `1`-truncation). Then, we can add abbreviations `SSet.Path.vertex/arrow`, so that `vertex` takes its values in `X _[0]`. Some API definitions and lemmas will to be duplicated, but the point is that there is only one underlying structure, and all the definitions/proofs for `SSet` should be one-liner applications of the corresponding API for `Truncated.SSet.Path`.

Thanks. I believe I have implemented this in commit [`149cb27`](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/20668/commits/149cb276b2d1a575ed0b698e7b3776ab6beff0b0), and everything seemed to work out well.
(well, everything except the simpNF linter).
Maybe the `spine` should be a def rather than abbrev?

I have changed `spine` and `map` to be defs at the `SSet` level, which allowed tagging the relevant lemmas `@[simp]` again. I also changed `interval` to be a def, because it seems to fit in the same category as `spine` and `map`. At the `SSet` level, we now have the following:
- `abbrev Path`
- `abbrev vertex`
- `abbrev arrow`
- `def interval`
- `def map`
- `def spine`

My thought is that this should be the right mix of reducibility to keep `dsimp` from dropping down to the `SSet.Truncated` level when you are trying to work at the `SSet` level. But, it may still need some tweaking.

You can see in [`bebab82`](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/20668/commits/bebab8276d34aee450b924fcd0cdcf9ea8f08dfd) that the change mentioned above allowed removing some extra `dsimp` truncation lemmas from one spot where I don't think we should need to deal with truncation. I do wish I had some more examples of this to experiment with, though.

Another thought -- Maybe `Path‚ÇÅ` should be private? We would need to add constructors `SSet.Path.mk` and `SSet.Truncated.Path.mk`, but it might make it easier to identify the places where the API falls short.
These lemmas (as well as `truncation_comp_trunc`) do not seem to be used yet. Instead (or in addition to these), could you add the natural isos versions of these lemmas?
I elected to replace the existing lemmas with natural iso versions of the same name. Maybe we want to name these `incl_comp_inclusion_iso` in case we later decide we also want the equalities, though?
We probably want some `simp` lemmas attached to this definition.
We probably want to deduce a `IsStrictSegal` instance from this definition.
